  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks to Consider</h2>
  <p>Our model may miss critical qualitative factors. Here are upside and downside risks for CVS.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Medicare Advantage Margin Recovery:</strong> If CVS (Aetna) can successfully reprice its Medicare Advantage plans and improve Star Ratings, margins could expand significantly faster than modeled.</li>
    <li><strong>Synergies Realized:</strong> Faster or deeper cost synergies realized from the Oak Street Health and Signify Health acquisitions.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Paydown:</strong> Accelerated debt reduction would directly transfer enterprise value to equity value, pushing the per-share intrinsic value higher.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Pressures:</strong> Increased scrutiny on Pharmacy Benefit Managers (PBMs) like Caremark could lead to legislation that compresses profits.</li>
    <li><strong>Retail Headwinds:</strong> Continued shrink (theft), front-store sales declines, and pharmacy reimbursement pressures negatively impacting retail margins.</li>
    <li><strong>High Debt Load:</strong> CVS carries significant debt (over $60B) from its acquisitions. In a higher-for-longer interest rate environment, refinancing this debt could compress FCF.</li>
  </ul>

