      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate reflects the risk of the cash flows. A {discountRate * 100}% rate includes the 10-year treasury yield of {riskFreeRate}% plus a premium for holding CVS equity, balancing their stable, non-cyclical healthcare demand against their high debt load and regulatory risks.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the heavy debt load affect the valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Debt is subtracted directly from Enterprise Value. CVS's massive debt load (over $60B) significantly depresses its Equity Value. If CVS didn't have this debt, the intrinsic value per share would be much higher.</div>
